Name: Quasi War
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Undeclared Naval War with France. This contest included land actions, such as that in the Dominican Republic, city of Puerto Plata, where marines captured a French privateer under the guns of the forts. Congress authorized military action through a series of statutes.

Name: First Barbary War
Objective: Policy change; Economic protection; Protect own Diplomatic interests
Description: Tripoli. The First Barbary War included the USS George Washington and Philadelphia affairs and the Eaton expedition, during which a few marines landed with United States Agent William Eaton to raise a force against Tripoli in an effort to free the crew of the Philadelphia. Tripoli declared war on the United States on May 10, 1801, and although Congress authorized U.S. military action by statute, they never voted on a formal declaration of war.

Name: Arrest of Pike's Expedition
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: Captain Z. M. Pike, with a platoon of troops, invaded Spanish territory at the headwaters of the Rio Grande on orders from General James Wilkinson. He was made prisoner without resistance at a fort he constructed in present-day Colorado, taken to Mexico, and later released after seizure of his papers.

Name: Gulf of Mexico Pirates
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Gulf of Mexico. American gunboats operated from New Orleans against Spanish and French privateers

Name: Annexation of West Florida
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Acquire Territory; Economic Protection; Protect own    Military Interests
Description: West Florida (Spanish territory). Governor William Charles Cole Claiborne of Louisiana, on orders of the President, occupied with troops territory in dispute east of the Mississippi River as far as the Pearl River, later the eastern boundary of Louisiana. He was authorized to seize as far east as the Perdido River.

Name: Patriot War
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Acquire Territory; Economic Protection; Protect own    Military Interests
Description: Amelia Island and other parts of east Florida, then under Spain. Temporary possession was authorized by President Madison and by Congress, to prevent occupation by any other power; but possession was obtained by General George Matthews in so irregular a manner that his measures were disavowed by the President.

Name: War of 1812
Objective: Aquire/Defend Territory; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: War of 1812. On June 18, 1812, the United States declared war between the United States and the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland. Among the issues leading to the war were British interception of neutral ships and blockades of the United States during British hostilities with France.

Name: Occupation of West Florida
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Maintain an Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: West Florida (Spanish territory). On authority given by Congress, General Wilkinson seized Mobile Bay in April with 600 soldiers. A small Spanish garrison gave way. The United States advanced into disputed territory to the Perdido River, as projected in 1810. No fighting.

Caribbean. Engagements between pirates and American ships or squadrons took place repeatedly, especially ashore and offshore about Cuba, Puerto Rico, Santo Domingo, and Yucatan. Three thousand pirate attacks on merchantmen were reported between 1815 and 1823. In 1822, Commodore James Biddle deployed a squadron of two frigates, four sloops of war, two brigs, four schooners, and two gunboats in the West Indies.

Spanish Florida. General Andrew Jackson took Pensacola Bay and drove out the British, in September 1814 with whom the United States was at war and pacified the Spanish governor of Florida. This capture of Pensacola was crucial to Jackson securing victory during the battle of New Orleans in November 1814.

Name: Second Barbary War
Objective: Maintain Empire; Policy Change; Economic Protection
Description: Algiers. The second Barbary War was declared against the United States by the Dey of Algiers of the Barbary states, an act not reciprocated by the United States. Congress did authorize a military expedition by statutes. A large fleet under U.S. Commodore Stephen Decatur attacked Algiers and obtained indemnities. Tripoli. After securing an agreement from Algiers, Decatur demonstrated with his squadron at Tunis and Tripoli, where he secured indemnities for offenses during the War of 1812.

Name: First Seminole War
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory; Economic Protection
Description: Spanish Florida—First Seminole War. The Seminole Indians, whose area was a haven for escaped slaves and border ruffians, were attacked by troops under Generals Andrew Jackson and Edmund P. Gaines and pursued into northern Florida. Spanish posts were attacked and occupied, British citizens executed. In 1819, the Floridas were ceded to the United States.

Name: Amelia Island Affair
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Acquire/Defend Territory; Economic Protection
Description: Amelia Island (Spanish territory off northeast Florida). Under orders of President James Monroe, United States forces landed and expelled a group of smugglers, adventurers, and freebooters.

Name: Oregon Territory claims
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: Oregon. The USS Ontario landed at the Columbia River and in August took possession of the Oregon territory. Britain had ceded sovereignty but Russia and Spain asserted claims to the area.

West Florida-Originally the Seminole war, this 1818 invasion of Spanish Florda (specifically, West Florida) eventually grew into a conflict between Spanish garrisons and Andrew Jackson's troops.  The two-and-one-half month conflict ended in an assault on the Spanish fort at Barrancas.

Name: African Slave Trade Mission
Objective: Acquire Territory; Social Protection & Order
Description: Africa. Naval units raided the slave traffic pursuant to the Act of 1819 by Congress which authorized U.S. armed vessels to interdict slave traders in an attempt to stop slave trade at its source and return slaves to Africa.

Name: Landings to Suppress Piracy
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Cuba. United States naval forces suppressing piracy landed on the northwest coast of Cuba and burned a pirate station.

Name: Landings in Cuba to Suppress Piracy (II)
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Cuba. Brief landings in pursuit of pirates occurred April 8 near Escondido; April 16 near Cayo Blanco; July 11 at Siquapa Bay; July 21 at Cape Cruz; and October 23 at Camrioca.

Name: Landings in Cuba to Suppress Piracy (III)
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Cuba. In October the USS Porpoise landed bluejackets near Matanzas in pursuit of pirates.

Name: Fajardo Affair
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Military Interests
Description: Puerto Rico (Spanish territory). Commodore David Porter with a landing party of 200 attacked the town of Fajardo, which had sheltered pirates and insulted American naval officers forcing an apology. Commodore Porter was later court-martialed for overstepping his authority.

Name: Piracy Battle
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Cuba. During March, cooperating American and British forces landed at Sagua La Grande, along the north coast of the Villa Clara province, to capture pirates.

Name: Anti-Piracy Operations in the Cyclades
Objective: Humanitarian Intervention, Economic Protection
Description: Greece. In October and November landing parties hunted pirates on the Mediterranean islands of Argentiere, Miconi, and Androse.

Name: First Sumatran Expedition
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Sumatra. February 6 to 9. A naval force landed and stormed a fort to punish natives of the town of Quallah Battoo for plundering the American ship Friendship.

Name: Landing to Protect Foreign Interests During Unrest
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: October 31 to November 15. A force was sent ashore at Buenos Aires to protect the interests of the United States and other countries during an insurrection.
Colombia seized US schooner Andrew Jackson.  Ship seized off the coast of Columbia and taken to Cartagena. Inferior court ruled in favor of seizure, overturned by appellate court.
United States sought damages for several American merchant ships seized during French Revolution.  After French refused to pay, United States began naval preparations.

Name: Ingham Incident
Objective: Economic Protection; Social Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Tensions between the United States and Mexico were high over California and Texas tensions.  Countries went into negotiations.

Name: Protection of the American Consulate in in Callao and Lima
Objective: Maintain Empire; Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: December 10, 1835, to January 24, 1836, and August 31 to December 7, 1836. Marines protected American interests in Callao and Lima during an attempted revolution.

Name: General Gaines in Nacogdoches
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory; Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection
Description: During Texas war for independence, President Andrew Jackson dispatched an American force led by General E.P. Gaines to Natchitoches, Louisiana, to prevent any incursions by Texas, Mexico, or Indians into American territory.

Name: General Urrea Incident
Objective: Maintain Empire, Economic Protection
Description: After Texas insurrection, several diplomatic incidents involving Mexico and United States Navy followed for next few years.

Name: The Caroline Affair
Description: Canadian troops seized and burned the Caroline, an American ship that was being used to supply Candian rebels who had taken refuge on an island in the Niagara River.  American troops were moved to the border in response.

Name: Second Sumatran Expedition
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Sumatra. December 24, 1838, to January 4, 1839. A naval force landed to punish natives of the towns of Quallah Battoo and Muckie (Mukki) for depredations on American shipping.
Mexico built up forces in Matamoras, Mexico to invade Texas.  In response, United States warships moved to the mouth of the Rio Grande which Mexico declared to be an invasion.

Name: Aroostook War (Pork and Beans War)
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: This is the Aroostook War between United States and British in Canada.  Though a bloodless confrontation, tensions were high and troops were mobilized.  Boundry between United States and British Canadian provinces of New Brunswick and Quebec were at heart of dispute.

Name: Fiji punitive expedition
Objective: Maintain Empire; Economic Protection; Protect Military/Diplomatic interests
Description: Fiji Islands. July. Naval forces landed to punish natives for attacking American exploring and surveying parties.

Name: Battle of Drummond's Island
Objective: Humanitarian Intervention
Description: A naval party landed to avenge the murder of Navy Seaman John Anderson by the native warriors in Drummond Island, Kiribati

Name: Retaliation for treaty abrogation
Objective: Maintain Empire; Economic Protection; Protect Military/Diplomatic interests
Description: Samoa. February 24. A naval party landed and burned towns after the murder of an American sailor on Upolu Island. This was the second engagement with islanders of the Pacific Ocean during the United States Exploring Expedition.

Name: Capture of Monterey
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: Commodore Jones, American, falsely believed Mexico planning to cede California to Great Britain.  Took three vessels to Monterey and demanded surrender of Monterey fort, hoisted Americna flag over the castle.  Upon discovering the error, he returned control of the fort to Mexico.

Name: Landing to Protect Americans in Canton
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Sailors and marines from the USS St. Louis were landed after a clash between Americans and Chinese at the trading post in Canton (now Guangzhong).

Mexican-American War fought over territories that now comprise the current American states of California, Texas, New Mexico, and Arizona.  Americans initially reticent to commit large numbers of military personnel, but had soon overpowered Mexican forces.

Name: Mexican-American War
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: Mexican War. On May 13, 1846, the United States recognized the existence of a state of war with Mexico. After the annexation of Texas in 1845, the United States and Mexico failed to resolve a boundary dispute, and U.S. President James K. Polk said that it was necessary to deploy forces in Mexico to meet a threatened invasion.
America push into Oregon Territory controlled by British Empire.  Neither sides in a position to fight, issue was turned over to international negotiation.

United States entered into treaty negotiations with Mexico on tariffs and security for a proposed trade route.  Mexico objected to provisions, US threatened to send troops regardless but eventually relented.

Name: The Cardenas Expedition
Objective: Protect own military/diplomatic interests
Description: 50 Americans left on Cuba after raid launched by Spanish general failed.  US Secretary of State urged for war but President opted for diplomatic solution.  However, US sent a warship to region to underscore gravity of situation.

Name: Freeing US merchant ship
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Johanns Island (east of Africa). August. Forces from the U.S. sloop of war USS Dale exacted redress for the unlawful imprisonment of the captain of an American whaling brig

Name: Jaffa Massacre Deployment
Objective: Social Protection; Protect own Military/Diplomatic interests
Description: Turkey. After a massacre of foreigners (including Americans) at Jaffa in January, a demonstration by the Mediterranean Squadron was ordered along the Turkish (Levant) coast.

Name: Buenos Aires Protection
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Argentina. February 3 to 12, 1852; September 17, 1852, to April 1853. Marines were landed and maintained in Buenos Aires to protect American interests during a revolution.

Name: Lobos Islands Affair
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: American merchant wanted to take guano from Lobos Islands (Peru) without having to pay Peruvian authorities.  He appealed to US,  Secretary of State wrote to Secretary of navy, who sent squadron to the islands to protect Americans who wished to take guano.

Name: Koszta/Smyrna Affair
Objective: Protect own diplomatic interests
Description: Hungarian refugee in America intending to become American citizen briefly returned to Smyrna and was seized, held in Austrian brig-of-war.  American warship threatened to fire into the brig if Austrian ship attempt to depart from port.

Name: Perry Expedition
Objective: Policy Change
Description: Japan. Commodore Matthew C. Perry and his naval expedition made a display of force leading to the “opening of Japan.” Ryukyu and Bonin Islands. Commodore Perry on three visits before going to Japan and while waiting for a reply from Japan made a naval demonstration, landing marines twice, and secured a coaling concession from the ruler of Naha on Okinawa. Perry also held a naval demonstration in the Bonin Islands, an archipelago of over 30 subtropical and tropical islands over 600 miles south of Tokyo, with the purpose of securing facilities for commerce.

Name: Burning of San Juan Del Norte
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Nicaragua. March 11 to 13. U.S. forces landed to protect American lives and interests during political disturbances.

Name: Battle of Muddy Flat
Objective: Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Social Protection and Order; Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/ord Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. April 4 to June 15 to 17. American and English ships landed forces to protect American interests in and near Shanghai during Chinese civil strife
Nicaragua. July 9 to 15. Naval forces bombarded and burned San Juan del Norte (Greytown) to avenge an insult to the American Minister to Nicaragua.

Name: The Black Warrior Affair
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own military/and or diplomatic interests
Description: Spanish authorities detained American merchant ship Black Warrior in Havana, Cuba.  U.S. demanded Spain pay indemnity for those wronged.  Eventually, Spain agreed and no military action was taken by either sides.

Name: Bombardment of Greytown
Objective: Acquire Territory, Protecting Economic Interests, Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Government in Britain's Mosquito Coast (present day Nicaragua) attempted to arrest American for murder.  American minister refused to turn him over.  American ship ordered to protect Americans in the are and American captain attacked down and burned British consulate.

Name: Anti-Piracy Efforts in Shanghai and Ty-ho Bay
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: China. May 19 to 21. U.S. forces protected American interests in Shanghai and, from August 3 to 5, fought pirates near Hong Kong.

Name: Fiji Punitive Expedition
Objective: Maintain Empire; Economic Protection
Description: Fiji Islands. September 12 to November 4. An American naval force landed to seek reparations for depredations on American residents and seamen.

Name: Callahan's Raid
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory; Social Protection; Economic Protection
Description: Band of Americans crossed into Mexico to retrieve runaway slaves and stolen horses.  Mexico troops fought back.  American troops at Fort Duncan made show of force to deter the Mexican troops.

Name: 1855 Diplomatic Crisis Over Cuba
Objective: Social Protection and Order; Economic Protection; Protect Own Military or Diplomatic Interest
Description: Spanish-American hostilities over control of Cuba.  Spanish warship detained American vessel for 45 minutes, with a similar incident occuring several weeks before. Secretary of State told Spanish envoy such incidents would make it impossible to preserve peace.

Name: Protection of Foreign Nationals During Instability in Montevideo
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Uruguay. November 25 to 29. United States and European naval forces landed to protect American interests during an attempted revolution in Montevideo.

Name: Battle of the Barrier Forts
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. October 22 to December 6. U.S. forces landed to protect American interests at Canton (now Guangzhong) during hostilities between the British and the Chinese and to avenge an assault upon an unarmed boat displaying the United States flag.

Name: Isthmus Mail Tax
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Colombia decided to reimplement a tax on all mail transported across the Isthmus of Panama.  The United States threatened to resist by force.

Name: 1st U.S. Military Intervention into Panama
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Panama, Republic of New Grenada. September 19 to 22. U.S. forces landed to protect American interests during an insurrection.

Name: Show of Force in Gulf of Mexico
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: British vessel boarded an American mail ship.  United States protested stopping of the mail ship, and both countries increase their presence in Gulf of Mexico in shows of force.

Name: William Walker's Surrender
Objective: Protect Own Military And/Or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Nicaragua. April to May, November to December. In May, Commander C.H. Davis, with some marines, received the surrender of William Walker, who had been attempting to gain control of the country and protected his men from the retaliation of native allies who had been fighting Walker. In November and December of the same year, United States vessels Saratoga, Wabash, and Fulton opposed another attempt by William Walker to take control of Nicaragua. Commodore Hiram Paulding’s act of landing marines and compelling the removal of Walker to the United States was tacitly disavowed by Secretary of State Lewis Cass, and Paulding was forced into retirement.

Name: Fiji punitive expedition
Objective: Maintain Empire; Economic Protection
Description: Fiji Islands. October 6 to 16. A U.S. marine expedition burned a native village in retaliation for the murder of two American traders on the island of Waya.

Name: Paraguay Expedition
Objective: Policy Change; Economic Protection
Description: Paraguay. Congress authorized a naval squadron to seek redress for an attack on a naval vessel in the Parana River during 1855. Apologies were made after a large display of force
Peru seized two vessels belonging to citizens of the United States accused of illegally storing guano.  United States protested to Peruvian foreign minister.

Name: Response Jaffa Riots
Objective: Social Protection & Order
Description: Turkey. The Secretary of State requested a display of naval force along the Levant after a massacre at Jaffa and mistreatment elsewhere “to remind the authorities (of Turkey) of the power of the United States.”

Name: Forgotten Crisis of 1858
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: British officers in West Indian waters searched American ships suspected of carrying slaves. British fired on American ships in several instances.  US sent warships into Gulf of Mexico with orders to resist British actions.

Name: Landing During Instability in Uruguay
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Uruguay. January 2 to 27. Forces from two United States warships landed to protect American property during a revolution in Montevideo.

Name: Landing at Shanghai During Period of Unrest
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. July 31 to August 2. A naval force landed to protect American interests in Shanghai

Name: Kisembo Unrest
Objective: Social Protection & Order
Description: Angola, Portuguese West Africa. March 1. American residents at Kissembo called upon American and British ships to protect lives and property during problems with natives.

Name: Colombian Revolution Intervention
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Bay of Panama. Naval forces landed to protect American during a revolution.

Name: Border Incursions in Pursuit of Juan Cortina
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: President Buchanan ordered troops to cross border into Northern Mexican frontier to neutralize threat of Mexican bandits threatening American citizens.

Name: Battle of Anton Lizardo
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: United States sloop-of-war Saratoga and two steamers asked two Mexican steamers to show their colors.  Steamers refused and fired on American ship.  American ships attacked and captured both Mexican steamers.

Name: Mexican War of Reform
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Maintain Empire; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests;
Description: European countries want to intervene during Mexican civil war to force a settlement.  Special agent of US legation in Mexico, in note to Spanish ambassador to Mexico, threatened armed action if any country intervented or tried to establish European presence in Mexico.

Name: Trent Affair
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Trent Affair.  During civil war, union ship San Jacinto boarded British packet ship Trent and seized two confederate diplomats en route to Britian.  The confederate diplomats had been hoping to secure diplomatic recongition by the British.

Name: Shimonoseki Campaign
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Dispute refers to an array of issues between Western powers and Choshu-controlled southern Japan.  Americans upset antiforeign sentiment had resulted in Japanese open fire on foreign ships.  American involvment limited; hostilities between both sides escalated into naval skirmishes.

Objective: Economic protection
Description: Naval forces of the United States, Great Britain, France, and the Netherlands compelled Japan and the Prince of Nagato in particular to permit the Straits of Shimonoseki to be used by foreign shipping in accordance with treaties already signed

Several European states sought to take advantage of weakened US position during civil war by intervening in Latin America.  Spanish miltary seized Chincha Islands.  US Secretary of State issues a statement through American diplomat in Madrid warning Spain United States would not yield assent to Spain's actions in Western Hemisphere.

Name: The French Intervention in Mexico
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Acquire/Defend Territory; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: With end of American Civil War, United States increased pressure on France to withdraw from Mexico.  American force began making shows of force up and down rio grande.  Secretary of State sent a letter to France demanding withdrawal.

Name: The "Glorious Revolution" of the 9th
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: U.S. forces protected the lives and property of American residents during a revolution

Name: Blockade Dispute with Brazil
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interest
Description: American steamer Shamokin arrived at mouth of Paraguay river transporting American diplomat.  Brazilian blockading party intially prevented the ship from passing, but relented when the Americans reminded the admiral the ship was armed and prepared to fight.

Name: US Consul Protection
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interest
Description: U.S. forces punished an assault on the American consul at Newchwang

Name: Occupation of Matamoros
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Social Protection & Order;
Description: Mexico. To protect American residents, General Sedgwick and 100 men in November compelled the surrender of Matamoras. Three days later, he was ordered to withdraw and the act was repudiated by the President. Notes: The 100 troops is claimed to be 300 in primary sources.

Name: The Bombardment of Valparaiso
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Social Protection
Description: Anglo-American fleet anchored in Valparaiso, Chile, the country's principal port, during dispute between Spain and Chile.  Anglo-American force fled when Sapniards arrived.

Name: Presidential Transition Show of Force
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority
Description: Marines occupied Managua and Leon.

Name: Formosa Expedition
Objective: Social Protection & Order
Description: naval force landed and burned a number of huts to punish the murder of the crew of a wrecked American vessel.

Name: Chiriquí Intervention
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: April. U.S. forces protected passengers and treasure in transit at Aspinwall (Colón) in the absence of local police or troops on the occasion of the death of the president of Colombia.

Name: Boshin War
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Japan (Osaka, Hiolo, Nagasaki, Yokohama, and Negata). February 4 to 8, April 4 to May 12, June 12 and 13. U.S. forces were landed to protect American interests during the civil war in Japan.

Name: Montevideo Uprising
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Economic Protection; Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interest
Description: U.S. forces protected foreign residents and the customhouse dyring an insurrection at Montevideo.

Name: Dominican Republic Interference
Objective: Maintain Empire, Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Haiti sough to establish Monroe Doctrine in Carribean, attempted to interfer in Dominician affairs during civil unrest.  United States sent seven warships in November as a display of force against Haiti.

Name: Tianjin Massacre
Objective: Social Protection & Order
Description: Tianjin Massacre, two French ministers killed and four British and American churches burned.  Foreign gunboats anchored off Tianjin.
Hawaiian Islands. September 21. U.S. forces landed and placed the American flag at the Honolulu consulate at half-mast upon the death of Queen Kalama.

Name: Battle of Boca Teacapan
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: U.S. forces destroyed the pirate ship Forward, which had run aground in the Rio Tecapan.

Name: Korea Shipwreck Incident
Objective: Policy Change; Economic Protection
Description: A U.S. naval force attacked and captured five forts to punish natives for depredations on Americans, particularly for murdering the crew of the USS General Sherman and burning the schooner and for later firing on other American small boats taking soundings up the Salee River.

Name: Isthmus Revolutions
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: U.S. forces protected American interests during hostilities between local groups over control of the government of the State of Panama.

Name: Border Crossings by U.S. Troops
Objective: Maintain Empire; Acquire or Defend Territory; Economic Protection; Social Protection and Order
Description: Mexico. United States troops crossed the Mexican border repeatedly in pursuit of cattle thieves and other brigands. There were some reciprocal pursuits by Mexican troops into border territory. Mexico protested frequently. Notable cases were at Remolina in May 1873 and at Las Cuevas in 1875. While Washington often supported these excursions, formal agreements between Mexico and the United States, the first in 1882, finally legitimized such raids. They continued intermittently, with minor disputes, until 1896.

American vessel Virginius intercepted by Spanish Ship and taken to Cuba.  Ship used by Cuban rebels during bid for independence.  Almost all crew on ship sentenced to execution, British ship quickly dispatched to prevent further executions, as several crew members were British.  Spain-US relations suffered momentarily.

Name: Honolulu Courthouse Intervention
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Social Protection
Description: Hawaiian Islands. February 12 to 20. Detachments from American vessels were landed to preserve order and protect American lives and interests during the coronation of a new king.

Name: The USS Saranac in Mexico
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Economic Protection; Social Protection and Order
Description: Mexican military on the US border had been conducting guerrilla operations against Texas ranchers.  Texan lawman Leander H. McNelly assembled 41 men "McNelly Rangers" to restore law and order.  Rangers pursue Mexican guerillas, with continual flare-ups.

Name: Evacuation of Matamoros
Objective: Social Protection and Order
Description: Marines were sent to police the town of Matamoros temporarily to protect American citizens and property while it was without other government.
This is a show of force by the United States following Mexican proposals to colonize the island of Ciare, in the Gulf of California.

Venezuela sent a note to Washington about British military demonstrations at mouth of Orinoco River.  As part of Monroe Doctrine, US Secretary of State issued a statement that United States would not stand by if demonstrations were a precursor to British use of force to acquire Venezuelan territory.

Name: Alexandria intervention
Objective: Social Protection and Order; Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: American forces landed to protect American interests during warfare between British forces and Egyptians and the looting of the city of Alexandria by Arabs.

American citizen arrested in Haiti.  Escaped to Washington after two years in prison to present his case.  Secretary of State instructed the US minister to Haiti to follow through with previous order to threaten the use of force if matters were not resolved.

Name: War of the Pacific
Description: Italy, France, and GB threatened to intervene if Chile did not end its war with Peru.  An American representative also signed the memorandum but did so without permission from his government, which repudiated the declaration when it was released.  Should this be included in dataset?
Unclear from Gibler narrative how US was involved in this incident.

China sent new president to Korea, when Chinese, American, and British naval gunboats arrived off coast in response to rumors that leader of previous coup d'etat was returning to Korea along with Japanese forces.

Name: Rebel Takeover of Colón and Panama City
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Panama (Colón). January 18 and 19. U.S. forces were used to guard valuables in transit over the Panama Railroad and the safes and vaults of the Panama Railroad company during revolutionary activity. From March through May in the cities of Colón and Panama City, U.S. forces helped reestablish freedom of transit during revolutionary strife.
Mexican authorities detained Cutting, an editor from Texas who had published libel about Mexico's leader.  The United States protested, and he was eventually released.

Name: Samoan Crisis
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Dispute over colonial control of Samoa between Germany, US, and UK.  US sent three warships, although they were destroyed in a hurriance while waiting in the Apia harbor before any hostilities broke out.

Name: Haitian Revolution
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Diplomatic/Military Interests
Description: US ship Haytian Republic captured by Haiti during periods of civil unrest.  United States tried to remain neutral, but ended up sending two American warships to Port-Au-Prince to underscore American demands for the ship's release.

Name: Baby Riots
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: A naval force was sent ashore to protect American residents in Seoul during unsettled political conditions when an outbreak of the populace was expected.

Name: Protective mission
Objective: Maintain Empire; Economic protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Samoa. November 14, 1888, to March 20, 1889. U.S. forces were landed to protect American citizens and the consulate during a native civil war.

American president dispatched an American fleet to Port-au-Prince in an attempt to intimidate Haiti into lease the area of Mole Saint-Nicholas to the United States in order to establish a naval base.  Haiti refused.

Name: Coup attempt
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Hawaiian Islands. July 30 and 31. U.S. forces protected American interests at Honolulu during a revolution.

Name: Buenos Aires protective mission
Objective: Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: 1890 Argentina. A naval party landed to protect the U.S. consulate and legation in Buenos Aires.

Name: Chilean Civil War and the Baltimore Affair
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Chile. August 28 to 30. The USS Baltimore and USS San Francisco landed a party commanded by Captain William S. Muce, USMC, to guard the U.S. Consulate at Valparaiso during the Chilean civil war.

Name: Attempt to Lease Mole St. Nicolas
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: Black revolt on Navassa defeated.

Name: Hawaiian Coup Troop Landing
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests; Remove Foreign Regime
Description: Marines were landed ostensibly to protect American lives and property, but many believed actually to promote a provisional government under Sanford B. Dole. This action was disavowed by the United States.

Name: Havana Ranch Incident
Objective: Maintain Empire; Acquire or Defend Territory; Social Protection and Order
Description: Dispute over Chamizal tract of land which shifted into Mexico after several decades of Rio Grande change in course.  Mexico and United States sought a boundary commission to settle dispute over new territory.  While the commission was unsuccessful, tensions in the area eased.

Name: Rio de Janeiro Affair
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Brazil. January. A display of naval force sought to protect American commerce and shipping at Rio de Janeiro during a Brazilian civil war.

Name: Sino-Japanese War
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. In March 1894, Marines from the gunboat USS Monocacy provided an honor guard for the Chinese viceroy’s official visit to the U.S. consulate at Tientsin (now Tianjin).
China. A naval vessel was beached and used as a fort at Newchwang (now Yingkou) for protection of American nationals.

Name: Korea Crisis in Sino-Japanese War
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Korea. July 24, 1894, to April 3, 1896. A guard of marines was sent to protect the American legation and American lives and interests at Seoul during and following the Sino-Japanese War.

Name: Protective mission
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Nicaragua. July 6 to August 7. U.S. forces sought to protect American interests at Bluefields following a revolution.

Name: Bocas del Toro Landing
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Colombia. March 8 to 9. Lieutenant Ben Hebard Fuller led a landing party at Boca del Toro to protect American lives and property threatened by a political revolt.

Dispute between French and Dominican governments over murder of naturazlied Frenchman in private fights.  Dominican government turned to United States for assistance.  French and America both dispatched vessels to the harbor in Santo Domingo.

A spanish vessel fired upon the Allianca, an American steamship three miles off the eastern shore of Cuba.  United States protested the action and Spain relieved of command the captain of the offending vessel.
Colombia detained a US coconut boat, claiming customs violations.  The ship was released after a protest by the United States.

Name: Protective mission
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Nicaragua. May 2 to 4. U.S. forces protected American interests in Corinto during political unrest

Name: Marine stationing in Beijing and Tientsin
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. November 5, 1898, to March 15, 1899. U.S. forces provided a guard for the legation at Peking and the consulate at Tientsin during contest between the Dowager Empress and her son

Name: Protective mission
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Nicaragua. February 7 and 8. U.S. forces protected American lives and property at San Juan del Sur.
Seized from Spain, occupation continues.

Name: Spanish-American War
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Humanitarian Intervention; Economic Protection
Description: On April 25, 1898, the United States declared war with Spain. The war followed a Cuban insurrection against Spanish rule and the sinking of the USS Maine in the harbor at Havana.
Seized from Spain, still use as base.

Name: Protective mission
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: American and British naval forces were landed to protect national interests at San Juan del Norte, February 22 to March 5, and at Bluefields a few weeks later in connection with the insurrection of General Juan P. Reyes.

StateB primary target?: 1 (rebellion, but there was not separate Filipino state)
Name: The Philippine-American War
Objective: Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: U.S. forces protected American interests following the war with Spain and conquered the islands by defeating the Filipinos in their war for independence. Killing 600,000 Filipinos.

Name: War of Succession
Objective: Change foreign regime; Maintain Empire; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: American and British naval forces were landed to protect national interests and to take part in a bloody contention over the succession to the throne.

Name: Boxer Rebellion
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: American troops participated in operations to protect foreign lives during the Boxer rising, particularly at Peking. For many years after this experience, a permanent legation guard was maintained in Peking and was strengthened at times as trouble threatened.

Name: Anticipated Protective Mission
Objective: Social Protection & Order
Description: French attempting to extract unpaid loans from the Dominican Republic.  French moved several warships into Dominican harbors, U.S. also moved the a warship into the Dominican waters in case of conflict.

Name: Retaking Colón
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic  Interests
Description: Colombia (State of Panama). November 20 to December 4. U.S. forces protected American property on the Isthmus and kept transit lines open during serious revolutionary disturbances.

Name: Continued Isthmus Unrest
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic  Interests
Description: Colombia (State of Panama). September 17 to November 18. The United States placed armed guards on all trains crossing the Isthmus to keep the railroad line open, and stationed ships on both sides of Panama to prevent the landing of Colombian troops.

Name: Return to Bocas del Toro
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect Own Military and/or Diplomatic  Interests
Description: Colombia. April 16 to 23. U.S. forces protected American lives and property at Bocas del Toro during a civil war.

Name: Alaska Boundary Dispute
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: United States and United Kingdom agreed to a convetion of six jurists-three from both sides-to decide the issue of the Alaska-Canda border.

Name: Venezuelan Crisis
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Economic Protection; Intervention to Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Several European countries blockaded five Venezulean ports out of frustration for Venezulean refusal to pay debts.  United States intervened when the US Secretary of State negotiated an end to the blockade.
United States threatened to intervene in Brazil if the Brazilian government did not protect the "innocent" interests and investments of its citizens.

Name: US Recognition of Independent Panama
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime authority; Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Economic protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: United States angered Colombia rejected the Hay-Herran Convention, which would have leased land to America for construction of the Panama Canal.  After uprising in Panama City, U.S. sent warships to the area to prevent Colombia from compelling the Panamanians.

Name: Landing During 1903 Revolution
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Dominican Republic. March 30 to April 21. A detachment of marines was landed to protect American interests in the city of Santo Domingo during a revolutionary outbreak.

Name: The Skinner Mission to Ethiopia
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Abyssinia. Twenty-five marines were sent to Abyssinia to protect the U.S. Consul General while he negotiated a treaty.

Name: Conservative Rebellion of 1903
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection
Description: Honduras. March 23 to 30 or 31. U.S. forces protected the American consulate and the steamship wharf at Puerto Cortez during a period of revolutionary activity.

U.S. forces sought to protect American interests and lives during and following the revolution for independence from Colombia over construction of the Isthmian Canal. With brief intermissions, United States Marines were stationed on the Isthmus from November 4, 1903, to January 21, 1914, to guard American interests.

Name: Beirut intervention
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Syria. September 7 to 12. U.S. forces protected the American consulate in Beirut when a local Moslem uprising was feared.
Dispute number does not appear in Gibler book.

Name: The Seven Red Flags Battle
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Economic Protection; Intervention to Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: American and British naval forces established an area in which no fighting would be allowed and protected American interests in Puerto Plata and Sosua and Santo Domingo City during revolutionary fighting.

Name: Korea Crisis in Russo-Japanese War
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Korea. January 5, 1904, to November 11, 1905. A guard of Marines was sent to protect the American legation in Seoul during the Russo-Japanese War.

Name: Tangiers Hostages
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: A squadron demonstrated to force the release of a kidnapped Americans Ion Hanford Perdicaris and Cromwell Varley. Marines were landed to protect the consul general.

Name: Huerta's Resignation
Objective: Economic Protection; Protection of Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Panama. November 17 to 24. U.S. forces protected American lives and property at Ancon at the time of a threatened insurrection.

Chinese students began boycott of American goods which was eventually supported by Chinese government.  US government prepared for an "expedition" if necessary.  Chinense government no longer supported boycott, although it continued.

Name: Occupation of Cuba
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect Economic Interests, Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: U.S. forces sought to restore order, protect foreigners, and establish a stable government after serious revolutionary activity.

Name: Honduran Rebellion
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection
Description: Honduras. March 18 to June 8. To protect American interests during a war between Honduras and Nicaragua, troops were stationed in Trujillo, Ceiba, Puerto Cortez, San Pedro, Laguna, and Choloma.

Name: 1908 Panamanian Election
Objective: Economic Protection; Protection of Own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Marines intervene in election contest.

Name: Estrada’s Rebellion
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Build Foreign Regime Authority; Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection
Description: United States dispatched several navy vessels to Nicaragua due to rumors of revolutionary activity.  Various concerns among Latin American countries about military intentions of Nicaraguan president.

Name: Nicaraguan civil war
Objective: Social Protection; Economic Protection
Description: U.S. forces protected American interests at Bluefields

Name: Chinese Revolution
Objective: Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Social Protection and Order; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China's 1911 Revolution began in October 1911. Many troop deployments occurred between 1911 and 1913 to defend against potential damage from rebels or the Chinese government. Information relating to some deployments is weak or missing.
Dispute number does not appear in Gibler book.

Name: Rebellion Against Antoine Simon
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: The United States dispatched multiple warships to Haiti during a rebellion to protect American nationals and business interests.

Name: General Bonilla’s Counter-Rebellion
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Policy Change; Economic Protection
Description: Honduras. January 26. American naval detachments were landed to protect American lives and interests during a civil war in Honduras.

Name: The Mexican Revolution
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Maintain/Build Foreign Regime; Economic Protection; Social Protection and Order
Description: Disputes broke out between Mexican federal government and rebels, especially near U.S. Mexico border.  United States mobilized troops along the border and by sea.  President Taft issued a proclamation warning all within the United States not to take part in the Mexican revolution and to end the flow of weapons into Mexico.
China. August 24 to 26, on Kentucky Island, and August 26 to 30 at Camp Nicholson. U.S. forces protected Americans and American interests during revolutionary activity.

Name: Protection of Kentucky Island and Camp Nicholson
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. The disorders which began with the overthrow of the dynasty during Kuomintang rebellion in 1912, which were redirected by the invasion of China by Japan, led to demonstrations and landing parties for the protection of U.S. interests in China continuously and at many points from 1912 on to 1941. The guard at Peking and along the route to the sea was maintained until 1941. In 1927, the United States had 5,670 troops ashore in China and 44 naval vessels in its waters. In 1933 the United States had 3,027 armed men ashore. The protective action was generally based on treaties with China concluded from 1858 to 1901.

Name: Cuban rebels
Objective: Social Protection and Order, Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests, Protecting Economic Interests
Description: Cuba. June 5 to August 5. U.S. forces protected American interests on the Province of Oriente, and in Havana.

Name: Attempted Seizure at Puerto Cortez
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: Honduras. A small force landed to prevent seizure by the government of an American-owned railroad at Puerto Cortez. The forces were withdrawn after the United States disapproved the action.

Name: Liberal Uprising
Objective: Maintain Foreign Regime Authority; Social Protection; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Nicaragua. August to November 1912. U.S. forces protected American interests during an attempted revolution. A small force, serving as a legation guard and seeking to promote peace and stability, remained until August 5, 1925.

Name: 1912 Panama Election
Objective: Protect own Military/Diplomatic Interests
Description: Panama. U.S. troops, on request of both political parties, supervised elections outside the Canal Zone.

Name: Constantinople Intervention/1st Balkan War
Objective: Social Protection; Protect Economic interests; Protect Diplomatic Interests
Description: Turkey. November 18 to December 3. U.S. forces guarded the American legation at Constantinople during a Balkan War.
Mexico. September 5 to 7. A few marines landed at Ciaris Estero to aid in evacuating American citizens and others from the Yaqui Valley, made dangerous for foreigners by civil strife.

Name: Instability in the Dominican Republic
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Fight with rebels over Santo Domingo.

Dominican Republic. June and July. During a revolutionary movement, United States naval forces by gunfire stopped the bombardment of Puerto Plata, and by threat of force maintained Santo Domingo City as a neutral zone.

Name: Landings During Revolutionary Instability in Haiti
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Haiti. January 29 to February 9, February 20 to 21, October 19. Intermittently, U.S. naval forces protected American nationals in a time of rioting and revolution.
Mexico. Undeclared Mexican-American hostilities followed the Dolphin affair and Villa’s raids and included capture of Vera Cruz and later Pershing’s expedition into northern Mexico.
The United States protested Germany's decision to use submarine warfare to enforce a blockade around Britain.  German U-boats were responsible for attacks on five American ships.

Name: US Occupation of Haiti
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Haiti. July 28, 1915, to August 15, 1934. U.S. forces maintained order during a period of chronic political instability.

President Wilson threatened to intervene in Mexican Civil War.  President put an ambargo on arms sent to Mexico.  On July 30th, Wilson's peace plan put into effect with the full support of US government.

Name: Nanjing Incident (Nanking)
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection
Description: China. American forces landed to quell a riot taking place on American property in Nanking.

Name: Military Occupation
Objective: Social Protection; Protect Economic interests; Protect Diplomatic Interests
Description: Dominican Republic. May 1916 to September 1924. American naval forces maintained order during a period of chronic and threatened insurrection.

The United States sent a military expedition into Mexico to apprehend Mexican bandit Pancho Villa.  In addition to battling Villa's men, American troops clashed with Mexican regulars.  Expedition withdrew in failure after 11 months.

Name: WWI
Objective: Defend Territory; Policy Change; Economic Protection
Description: WWI.

Name: Chungking Incident
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. American troops were landed at Chungking to protect American lives during a political crisis.

Name: U.S. Force Deployment
Objective: Social Protection; Protect Economic interests; Protect Diplomatic Interests
Description: Cuba. U.S. forces protected American interests during an insurrection and subsequent unsettled conditions. Most of the United States Armed Forces left Cuba by August 1919, but two companies remained at Camaguey until February 1922.

Name: Seizure of German ships
Objective: Policy Change; Protecting Economic Interests; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: after attack on American shipping by German u-boats, US declares war on Germany and seizes German ships in American ports.

British blockading Sweden, demanding Sweden enter into a favorable trade status with Great Britain.  United States and Great Britain coordinated on Sweden question, although the blockade was made up entirely of British ships.

Name: The Adriatic Question
Objective: Social Protection
Description: Dalmatia. U.S. forces were landed at Trau at the request of Italian authorities to police order between the Italians and Serbs.

Name: Mexican Border Incidents
Objective: Social Protection & Order;
Description: Bandits fired into El Paso from Mexican side of border, American troops moved into Mexico to put down the bandits.  Secretary of State warned Mexico that if it could not protect Americans within its borders than a greater intervention was imminent.  Mexico urged US government to pull out of Mexico and threatened clashes with troops.  Small, unverified attacks occured between between troops, citizens, and bandits.
Mexico moved troops to the border after American patrols crossed the border in pursuit of bandits.  Clashes ensued after both sides dug in along the Rio Grande.

Name: Election Unrest and Chiriquí Rebellion
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Economic Protection; Social Protection and Order
Description: Panama. U.S. forces were used for police duty according to treaty stipulations, at Chiriqui, during election disturbances and subsequent unrest.

Soviet Russia. Marines were landed at and near Vladivostok in June and July to protect the American consulate and other points in the fighting between the Bolshevik troops and the Czech Army, which had traversed Siberia from the western front. A joint proclamation of emergency government and neutrality was issued by the American, Japanese, British, French, and Czech commanders in July. In August 7,000 men were landed in Vladivostok and remained until January 1920, as part of an allied occupation force. In September 1918, 5,000 American troops joined the allied intervention force at Archangel and remained until June 1919. These operations were in response to the Bolshevik revolution in Russia and were partly supported by Czarist or Kerensky elements.

Name: Vladivostok Marine deployment
Objective: Defend Territory; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Russia (Siberia). February 16, 1920, to November 19, 1922. A Marine guard was sent to protect the United States radio station and property on Russian Island, Bay of Vladivostok

Name: Tegucigalpa Uprising
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Social Protection and Order; Protect Economic Interests
Description: Honduras. September 8 to 12. A landing force was sent ashore to maintain order in a neutral zone during an attempted revolution.

Name: Allied Occupation of Ottoman lands
Objective: Protect own Military/Diplomatic Interests
Description: Turkey. Marines from the USS Arizona were landed to guard the U.S. Consulate during the Greek occupation of Constantinople.

Name: Kiukiang Incident
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. March 14. A landing force was sent ashore for a few hours to protect lives during a disturbance at Kiukiang.

Name: The Unionista Revolution
Objective: Economic Protection; Social Protection and Order
Description: Guatemala. April 9 to 27. U.S. forces protected the American legation and other American interests, such as the cable station, during a period of fighting between Unionists and the government of Guatemala.

Name: Election dispute
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Social Protection & Order
Description: Cuban election results inconclusive, both sides claimed victory and threatened violence.  President Wilson appointed General Crowder as special representative to Cuba.  State Department threatened military intervention if Cubans did not cooperate with Crowder.  Crowder arrived in Havana about US battleship as a show of force.

Name: Border dispute
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Economic Protection
Description: Panama-Costa Rica. American naval squadrons demonstrated in April on both sides of the Isthmus to prevent war between the two countries over a boundary dispute.

Name: Deterring War with Honduras
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority
Description: The United States sent a warship at the request of Honduras, which feared an invasion from El Salvador.

Name: Miscellaneous Landings
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. Between April 1922 and November 1923 marines were landed five times to protect Americans during periods of unrest.

Name: Evacuation during Greek-Turkish War
Objective: Social Protection and Order, Humanitarian Intervention, Protect own Military & Diplomatic interests
Description: Turkey. September and October. A landing force was sent ashore with consent of both Greek and Turkish authorities to protect American lives and property when the Turkish Nationalists entered Smyrna.

Name: Shanghai Landing
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. September. Marines were landed to protect Americans and other foreigners in Shanghai during Chinese factional hostilities.

Name: Honduran Civil War of 1924
Objective: Economic Protection; Social Protection and Order
Description: Honduras. February 28 to March 31, September 10 to 15. U.S. forces protected American lives and interests during election hostilities.

Name: De la Huerta Rebellion
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection
Description: Airpower defends Calles from rebellion

Name: Protection of Shanghai
Objective: Economic Protection
Description: China. January 15 to August 29. Fighting of Chinese factions accompanied by riots and demonstrations in Shanghai brought the landing of American forces to protect lives and property in the International Settlement.

Name: Uprising of 1925
Objective: Economic Protection; Social Protection and Order; Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority
Description: Honduras. April 19 to 21. U.S. forces protected foreigners at La Ceiba during a political upheaval.

Name: Panama Rent Riots
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Maintain Empire; Defend Territory; Social Protection; Economic Protection
Description: Panama. October 12 to 23. Strikes and rent riots led to the landing of about 600 American troops to keep order and protect American interests.

Name: Hankow deployment
Objective: Social Protection and Order; Economic Protection; Protect own Military & Diplomatic interests
Description: The U.S. deploys naval warships and marines to the U.S. Consulate in Wuhan after attacks by Chinese Nationalists intensify.

Name: Removal of Nicaraguan President/civil war
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Nicaragua. May 7 to June 5, 1926; August 27, 1926, to January 3, 1933. The coup d’état of General Chamorro aroused revolutionary activities leading to the landing of American marines to protect the interests of the United States. United States forces came and went intermittently until January 3, 1933.

Name: Nanjing Incident
Objective: Social Protection and Order; Protecting Economic Interests; Protect own Military & Diplomatic interests
Description: Riots broke out in Nanjing, which was controlled by Great Britian, mobs began attacking foreign nationals.  British and American warships responded, establishing themselves at the port.

Name: Las Limas Bombing
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority
Description: American marines based in Nicaragua bombed a Honduran village after being fired on by outlaws.

Name: Shanghai Incident
Objective: Social Protection and Order; Protect own Military & Diplomatic interests
Description: China. American forces were landed to protect American interests during the Japanese occupation of Shanghai.
Japanese aircraft attacked Chinese forces in Shanghai.  British and American forces sent to Shanghai to protect British and American nationals during the conflict.

Name: Communist Uprising
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests; Economic Protection; Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority
Description: Warships sent during Marti revolt.

Name: Cuban Revolution of 1933
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection
Description: Cuba. During a revolution against President Gerardo Machado naval forces demonstrated but no landing was made.

Name: Foochow Protective Mission
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: China. Marines landed at Foochow to protect the American Consulate.

Name: Panay Incident
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Japanese bombs sunk the Panay, an American gunboat, on the Yangtze during Japan's assault on Nanking.  Japanese later paid an indemnity and claimed they were unaware Panay was an American vessel.
Germany seized an American steamship accused of transporting contraband to Britain.  A prize crew took it to the Soviet port of Murmansk, where the Soviets detained the ship and everyone aboard.
Britian routinely seized mail from Germany to the United States.  United States protest and eventually the seizures stopped as British and American cooperation increased.

Name: Deterrence Campaign Against Japan
Objective: Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Japan asserted American naval maneuvers taking place in Pacific and near Philippines could be construed as acts of aggression.  Over next year and a half, numerous warnings and shows of force were made to Japan by the United States to stay out of Indochina and to maintain the status quo.

State B: Newfoundland, Bermuda, St. Lucia, BHM, JAM, AAB, TRI, British Guiana
Description: Newfoundland, Bermuda, St. Lucia, Bahamas, Jamaica, Antigua, Trinidad, and British Guiana. Troops were sent to guard air and naval bases obtained by negotiation with Great Britain. These were sometimes called lend-lease bases.
Germany pressed Bulgaria to renounce neutrality and join the Axis powers.  Bulgaria declared war on both United States and Britain.

United States detained 30 merchant ships and crews belonging to Axis powers.  Germany and Italy diplomatically protested seizures, United States rejected, contending seizures were legal.  United States also made decision to use Monroe Doctrine to put Greeland under protection of United States.  United States became more aggressive in confronting German vessels in the Atlantic.
Greenland. Greenland was taken under protection of the United States in April.
Iceland. Iceland was taken under the protection of the United States, with consent of its government, for strategic reasons.

State B: JPN, GMY, ITA, ROM, HUN, BUL
Name: WWII
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Defend Territory; Policy Change; Social Protection & Order; Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: WWII

Netherlands (Dutch Guiana). In November the President ordered American troops to occupy Dutch Guiana, but by agreement with the Netherlands government in exile, Brazil cooperated to protect aluminum ore supply from the bauxite mines in Surinam.
Dispute number does not appear in Gibler book.
Thailand declared war on Great Britain and the US and joined Japan in its attack on British Burma.
Dispute number does not appear in Gibler book.

Name: Operation Beleaguer
Objective: Build Foreign Regime Authority; Social Protection
Description: China. In October 50,000 U.S. Marines were sent to North China to assist Chinese Nationalist authorities in disarming and repatriating the Japanese in China and in controlling ports, railroads, and airfields. This was in addition to approximately 60,000 U.S. forces remaining in China at the end of World War II.

Name: Turkish Strait Crisis
Objective: Acquire/Defend Territory;Policy Change
Description: Turkey. On December 20, the Soviet Union demanded that Turkey cede 180 square miles of land along the Black Sea coast, as it was historically Georgian territory. The Soviet Union and Turkey mobilized troops. The United States threatened the Soviet Union with war in October 1946, and the Soviet Union backed down. (Gibler)

Name: Airspace Violations
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Protect own Military Interests
Description: Response to shoot-down of US plane.

Name: Uruguay Presidential Inauguration
Objective: Policy Change
Description: Bombers deployed as show of strength.

Merged with China 1945 above. Marines were dispatched to Nanking to protect the American embassy when the city fell to Communist troops, and to Shanghai to aid in the protection and evacuation of Americans.

Name: Greek Civil War
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: U.S. directs extreme-right in civil war. no combat troops but advisers went into combat - "aggressive assistance"

Name: Arab-Israeli Conflict  Evacuation
Objective: Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Palestine. A marine consular guard was sent to Jerusalem to protect the U.S. Consul General.

Name: Berlin Airlift
Objective: Humanitarian Intervention; Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: The Berlin Airlift. After the Soviet Union established a land blockade of the U.S., British, and French sectors of Berlin on June 24, 1948, the United States and its allies airlifted supplies to Berlin until after the blockade was lifted in May 1949.

China seized three American ships on September 29, 1949 for alleged enemy support. The Chinese seized the US embassy in Beijing in mid-January. The United States ordered all of their personnel out of China. (Gibler)

As a response to Chinese Nationalists' detainment, harrassment, and seizing of ships, the United States sent warships as escorts for its commercial vessels and stated that the Chinese government would be held responsible for the various acts. (Gibler)

Name: Yugaslavian Split from Eastern Bloc
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Acquire/Defend Territory; Policy Change
Description: In response to diplomatic provocations and troop buildup between the USSR and Yugoslavia, the United States dispatched its largest peacetime fleet into the Mediterranean to observe the affairs.

Name: Korean War
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Acquire Defend Territory
Description: Korean War--NYT

Name: Jayuya Uprising
Objective: Maintain Empire
Description: Independence rebellion crushed in Ponce.

Name: Huk Rebellion
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority
Description: Huk. Rebel--NYT

Name: U.S. Protection of Taiwan
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Policy Change; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Grossman: U.S./So. Korea fights China/No. Korea to stalemate; A-bomb threat in 1950, and against China in 1953. Still have bases.
Ecuador seized and released several American fishing boats for illegally fishing in Ecuadorian waters.

Name: Air interdictions with China and Russia
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: American fighters shot down a Soviet passenger plan along the Chinese-Korean frontier. The United States blamed the Soviets for sending a passenger plane so close to the area of hostilities. Two days later, two Soviet fighters downed an American B-50 bomber off the coast of Siberia. the Soviets accused the American bomber of violating its airspace, which the Americans denied. (Gibler)

Name: Aircraft Interception
Objective: Maintain Empire; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: The Czechs shot down an American plane, and Soviet MiGs shot down a British bomber over the Elbe River valley. (Gibler)

Name: Coup in Iran
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Policy Change; Economic Protection

The 1,000 US marines already in Thailand for bilateral training were also moved to the border.  The United States and Soviets supplied the fighting forces and guarded their interests in the region.

Series of incidents between North and South Korea.  Firefight broke out when Vasily Matuzok, a Soviet defector, ran across the demilitarized zone.  Three North Koreans and one South Korean were killed in the incident. Not sure if we want to include this as a case of usage of force.
The Soviet Union seized an Alaskan fishing vessel and five of her crew.  The crew were held for a week before being returned to the United States.

A Czechoslovakian jet crossed into West German airspace and fired on US helicopter on routine surveillance mission.  After firing two missiles at Helicopter, jet return to Czech airspace.  Helicopter and crew unharmed.  United States filed a formal protest with Czechoslovakian government next day.  No other action taken.

Soviet countermeasures against American and British reconnaissance efforts in East Germany.  First, Soviet forces killed an American soldier in East Germany.  United States protested the shooting.  Several months later, two American soldiers were detained by Soviet troops inside East Germany.

Name: Iran - Iraq War
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Maintain Empire; Acquire/Defend Territory; Policy Change; Economic Protection;
Description: At end of 1985, growing antagonism between Iran and other Gulf States that began siding with or aiding Iraq forces during war with iran.  The United States warned Iraq against spreading the War.  US also warned Iran that if hostilities were carried to other Gulf States it would be "a major threat to US interests."

Name: Achille Lauro Hijacking
Objective: Humanitarian Intervention
Description: Italy. On October 10, 1985, U.S. Navy pilots intercepted an Egyptian airliner and forced it to land in Sicily. The airliner was carrying the hijackers of the Italian cruise ship Achille Lauro, who had killed an American citizen during the hijacking.

Name: Libya-Egypt border tensions
Objective: Maintain/Build Foreign Regime Authority; Acquire/Defend Territory
Description: US put its forces in region on high alert as commanders feared that a full-scale conventional war may break out between Egypt and Libya.

Name: Drug seizure in Bolivia
Objective: Social Protection and Order
Description: Bolivia. U.S. Army personnel and aircraft assisted Bolivia in anti-drug operations.

Name: Sonic Boom event
Objective: Maintain Empire
Description: During a Cuban military exercise, the United States sent an SR-71 reconnaissance jet low over Cuban territory, breaking sound barrier with a sequence of roaring booms.  Foreign diplomats saw the action as a show of force, and Cuba sent a note of protest to the United States.  Hundreds of thousands of Cubans protested outside US mission to Havana.

Name: U.S. Mechant Siezure
Objective: Economic Protection; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Iranian ships searched an American ship near the Persian Gulf that was suspected of providing material to Iraq.  The search lasted less than an hour, but formal protest was immediately issued by the United States, which also released two navy ships to the area. US intervenes on side of Iraq in war, defending reflagged tankers and shooting down civilian jet. This is an aggregation of MIDs 2578 and 2740.

Objective: Policy Change; Protect own Military and/or Diplomatic Interests
Description: Anti-Lib. Bombing--FAf/NYT/ 2 Libyan gun boats sunk, SAM missile site

US used Sandinista attacks on Contra rebel bases as pretext/ no combat

1982 Law of Sea Convention gave foreign naval vessels the right of innoncent passage through territorial waters.  In 1983, Soviet government updated law, limiting areas of passages.  Two US Navy vessels passed through Soviet territorial waters in the Black Sea.  In a note of protest, the USSR stated American vessels disregarded repeated warnings.  US government responded to allegations by defending the ships' right to innocent passage.

The USSR placed three ships-an electronic intelligence-gathering vessel and two destroyers-30 to 80 miles off the Israeli coast.  Pentagon officials reported this number as six warships and 20 auxiliary ships.  This show of force came amid confrontations between the United States and Libya.
US intervenes on side of Iraq in war, defending reflagged tankers and shooting down civilian jet. Case is merged into Iran 1986.

Name: USS Stark Incident
Objective: Protect own Diplomatic or Military Interests
Description: Iraqi aircraft unintentionally struck an American warship in the Persian Gulf.  Missile caused extensive damage to the ship and result in the death of 37 sailors.  The United States did not retaliate or return fire, but diplomats issue strong warnings to Iraq that it would fire upon any aircraft or vessel that appeared ready to attack in the future.  Saddam Hussein issued a statement that tok responsibility for the attack and Iraq agreed to pay compensation for damage and loss of life.

Name: Political Unrest
Objective: Social Protection & Order; Policy Change
Description: Noriega Dispute--NYT

A US warship was escorting oil tankers, and an Iraqi warplane approached.  The American vessel shot twon warning flares.  The Iraqi warplane responded with firing two missiles that streaked off the ship.

Name: Downing of Libyan Jets
Objective: Protect own Diplomatic or Military Interests
Description: Grossman: Two Libyan jets shot down.

Canadian Forces frigate and an American fishing vessel collided in US territorial waters.  Canada claimed fishing vessel had violated Canadian territorial waters.  Fishing vessel ignored the Canadian frigate's demand to yield, at which time the frigate fired several shots across the vessel's bow.

Name: Andean Initiative War on Drugs
Objective: Social Protection and Order
Description: Andean Initiative in War on Drugs. On September 15, 1989, President Bush announced that military and law enforcement assistance would be sent to help the Andean nations of Colombia, Bolivia, and Peru combat illicit drug producers and traffickers. By mid-September there were 50-100 U.S. military advisers in Colombia in connection with transport and training in the use of military equipment, plus seven Special Forces teams of 2-12 persons to train troops in the three countries.

Name: Operation Just Cause
Objective: Remove Foreign Regime; Social Protection
Description: US removes Panamanian government (WP, NYT)/ maintained objective until escalation to Just Cause intervention
